title: Enhancing OOD Detection Using Latent Diffusion

sections.text:
#### Abstract

Numerous Out-of-Distribution (OOD) detection algorithms have been developed to identify unknown samples or objects in real-world deployments. One line of work related to OOD detection propose utilizing auxiliary datasets to train OOD detectors, thereby enhancing the performance of OOD detection. Recently, researchers propose to leverage Stable Diffusion (SD) to generate outliers in the pixel space, which may complicate network training. To mitigate this issue, we propose an Outlier Aware Learning (OAL) framework, which synthesizes OOD training data in the latent space. This improvement enables us to train the network with only a few synthesized outliers. Besides, to regularize the model's decision boundary, we develop a mutual information-based contrastive learning module (MICL) that amplifies the distinction between In-Distribution (ID) and collected OOD features. Moreover, we develop a knowledge distillation module to prevent the degradation of ID classification accuracy when training with OOD data. Extensive experiments on CIFAR-10/100 benchmarks demonstrate the superior performance of our method.

## 1. Introduction

Out-of-Distribution (OOD) detection is a crucial component for deploying models in the real world [51], which has drawn increasing attention in the machine learning safety community [30]. To prevent modern neural networks from being over-confident for OOD inputs and producing untrustworthy predictions [12, 34], several studies proposed training the model with an auxiliary dataset [16] and regularizing the model to learn a compact decision boundary between

Here, $\hat{\mathbf{v}}$ represents the OOD embeddings sampled from a vision model's feature space by k-Nearest Neighbor (k-NN) [19], $f^{\text {mod }}$ denotes OOD latent embeddings transformed from the latent representation generated by Diffusion model, $f^{\text {trn }}$ denotes the in-distribution feature of the downstream model. We enlarge the discrepancy between $f^{\text {trn }}, f^{\text {mod }}$ and $\hat{\mathbf{v}}$ using MICL, thereby effectively regularizing the model's decision boundary.
in-distribution and out-of-distribution data [10, 11]. These methods demonstrate superior OOD detection performance compared with those that do not use auxiliary datasets for training [10, 11]. The main challenges for these approaches include: (i) how to collect representative OOD samples for outlier exposure training, and (ii) developing algorithms to effectively regularize the model using the generated OOD data.

In recent work, VOS [10] proposes a latent-based approach that synthesizes outliers in the low-density region of the In-Distribution (ID) feature space and uses energybased loss functions to regularize the model. In NPOS [46], the authors also propose a latent-based synthesis framework. However, different from VOS, they mitigate the issue of the

strong assumption on the model's ID feature space by using non-parametric nearest neighbor distance-based methods.

To generate photo-realistic OOD data, enabling us to understand the synthesized outliers in a human-compatible manner, Dream-OOD [11] first propose to leverage Stable Diffusion [36] model to synthesize outlier images for training in the pixel space, marking a milestone in OOD detection. However, as empirically shown in VOS [10], synthesizing images in the high dimensional pixel space can be difficult to optimize [51]. Therefore, it is natural to design a method that uses diffusion models to generate outliers in the latent space for facilitating outlier exposure training.

Moreover, we find that in Dream-OOD[11], the ID accuracy may decrease after introducing the generated OOD data for training, even though the mean AUROC is improved. We also find similar phenomena in other outlier synthesis approaches, like VOS [10] (see experiment results in Figure 2). Nevertheless, the process of outlier exposure training must not harm the in-distribution classification accuracy [51].

Motivated by these findings, we develop an Outlier Aware Learning (OAL) framework, aiming to take a further step to study how to leverage Stable Diffusion to develop latentbased synthesis approaches that generate outlier data in the feature space for OOD supervision. We also develop a series of learning algorithms to improve OOD detection performance without compromising the ID accuracy. Specifically, to avoid making no assumptions on the ID feature space, we still utilize the k-Nearest Neighbor [19] method to sample outliers from the penultimate layer of a vision model. Then, to reduce the overall training time, we directly sample outliers from a pre-trained Transformer [8] encoder, which has already achieved superior performance on the in-distribution classification task. Afterward, we take these k-NN sampled outliers as token conditions for Stable Diffusion to generate samples for OOD supervision. Different from Dream-OOD [11], our approach synthesizes outliers in the latent space, which facilitates the training to a great extent. To be specific, our approach outperforms Dream-OOD on the CIFAR-100 benchmark using only a very small batch of OOD data gen-
erated using Stable Diffusion.
For regularizing the model, we develop a Mutual Information-based Contrastive Learning module (MICL) that enlarges the discrepancy between the ID and OOD data in the latent space, which is far better than the energy-based regularization methods [10]. The intuition of this approach is illustrated in Figure 1. We treat the mutual information between ID and OOD samples as a signal to increase the distance between them in an aligned feature space, making the ID features and OOD features increasingly independent of each other.

Moreover, inspired by the success of applying knowledge distillation in autonomous driving [18], we develop a simple yet effective knowledge distillation module to boost the in-distribution classification performance, named as IDKD (In-Distribution Knowledge Distillation). This module helps us to improve the model's ability to detect OOD samples while preventing degradation of its ID performance. Our experiments on CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 [20] benchmarks achieve non-trivial improvement in OOD detection performance, compared to both the post hoc methods and other outlier synthesis-based methods.

The main contributions of our paper can be summarized as follows:

- We propose an Outlier Aware Learning (OAL) framework, which generates OOD data from the latent space of Stable Diffusion, thereby facilitating network training using very small amount of synthesized outliers.
- We develop a mutual information-based contrastive learning module (MICL) to better regularize the model's decision boundary between the ID and OOD data. Additionally, we propose a knowledge distillation module named IDKD to boost ID classification performance while enhancing the model's ability to detect OOD samples.
- We conduct extensive experiments on the CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 benchmarks. The results demonstrate that our approach achieves superior performance on various challenging OOD datasets, verifying the effectiveness of our diffusion-based outlier synthesis method.

## 2. Related Work

Outlier exposure-based OOD detection. The outlier exposure-based approaches leverage auxiliary datasets to train the model, thereby improving the model's OOD detection performance [16]. In VOS [10], Du et al. propose to synthesize OOD data automatically from a class-conditional distribution in the model's ID feature space and develop an energy-based loss function to regularize the model. In NPOS [46], the authors argue that the class-conditional Gaussian distribution assumption for the model's ID feature space is too restrictive and may not hold for more complex situations in the open world. Therefore, they propose to use a nonparametric k-Nearest Neighbor distance-based approach to

sample outliers from the model's ID feature space. In DreamOOD [11], the authors first propose a Stable Diffusion-based [36] approach to synthesize photo-realistic OOD images which is easier for humans to understand than those latentbased synthesis approaches [10, 46].

In our study, different from Dream-OOD [11], we synthesize outliers from the latent space of the Stable Diffusion model, which facilitates the model's training.
Representation learning-based OOD detection. Another line of work leveraged representation learning techniques [3] to enhance the model's OOD detection performance. Sehwag et al. [39] and Winkens et al. [48] empirically demonstrate the effectiveness of representation learning techniques in OOD detection through contrastive learning methods. CSI [45] contrasts samples with distributionally shifted augmentations of themselves and introduces a new detection score adapted to this learning framework. SIREN [9] develop a trainable loss function to shape the representation into a mixture of vMF distribution [29] on the unit hyper-sphere and propose a new OOD score based on the learned classconditional vMF distributions.

In our research, we investigate the application of knowledge distillation in OOD detection, verifying its effectiveness in both preventing ID accuracy degradation and enhancing OOD detection performance in the context of image classification tasks.
Diffusion models in OOD detection. Inspired by nonequilibrium thermodynamics, the Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DPM) was proposed to model the data distribution that enables precise sampling and evaluation of probabilities [40]. Afterward, plenty of variants of the DPM have been proposed, such as DDPM [17], NCSNs [41], DDPM++ [42], and so forth. Nowadays, DPM has achieved great successes in many sorts of vision tasks, including image generation [7, 37], image inpainting [1, 28] and image segmentation [2, 49], etc. In respect of OOD detection, many researchers propose to use diffusion models to perform outlier detection. For instance, in [13], the authors apply DDPMs to perform unsupervised OOD detection, which leverages the reconstruction error metrics to confirm whether an image is OOD. DIFFGUARD [13] uses the guidance from semantic mismatch to better discern ID samples from the OOD ones. LMD [27] utilizes the diffusion model's manifold mapping ability to conduct unsupervised OOD detection.

Within our research, we explore the application of Stable Diffusion [36] in synthesizing OOD data in the latent space.

## 3. Methodology

Our OAL training framework is shown in Figure 3. In brief, it primarily addresses the following issues: (1) how to effectively collect and train with outliers synthesized by Stable Diffusion in the latent space; (2) how to mitigate the degradation of ID performance when training with the generated

OOD data. The whole workflow of OAL consists of 2 stages. In Stage 1, we utilize the ID embeddings extracted from a pre-trained teacher model as input for the k-NN algorithm to sample class-conditioned OOD embeddings. Then, we use Stable Diffusion [36] to further generate OOD latent embeddings for OE training. In Stage 2, we develop MICL and IDKD modules to effectively regularize the model using the synthesized OOD data. Finally, we use the model trained by OAL to perform OOD inference. In the following sections, we will introduce our framework with equations and reveal more details of our contributions.

### 3.1. Preliminaries

Let $\mathcal{X}$ denote the in-distribution input image space, $\mathcal{Y}=$ $\{1,2, \cdots, C\}$ denote the label space. We consider the multi-classification task using a standard dataset denoted by $D=\left\{\left(\mathbf{x}_{i}, y_{i}\right)\right\}_{i=1}^{N}$, which is drawn i.i.d. from the joint data distribution $P_{\mathcal{X} \mathcal{Y}}^{i n}$, where $N$ is the number of samples, $\mathbf{x}_{i} \in \mathcal{X}, y_{i} \in \mathcal{Y}, i=1, \cdots, N$.
OOD detection. When deploying a machine learning model in the real world, a reliable classifier should not only classify ID samples, but also accurately identify OOD samples.

Formally, given a test sample $\mathbf{x}$ and a pre-trained classifier $f(\cdot)$, an OOD detection decision function can be written as

$$
\mathcal{G}(\mathbf{x} ; f)=\left\{\begin{array}{cc}
\text { ID, } & S(\mathbf{x} ; f) \geq \alpha \\
\text { OOD, } & S(\mathbf{x} ; f)<\alpha
\end{array}\right.
$$

where $\alpha$ is the threshold, ID represents that sample $\mathbf{x}$ comes from the in-distribution dataset and OOD means that the sample $\mathbf{x}$ comes from the out-of-distribution dataset. $S(\mathbf{x} ; f)$ is the score function.
Stable Diffusion model. To make the computation and training of diffusion models more efficient, in [36], the authors proposed using an encoder $\mathcal{E}(\cdot)$ to compress the input images into a latent representation $\mathbf{z}=\mathcal{E}(\mathbf{x}), \mathbf{z} \in \mathbb{R}^{c \times h \times w}$. Then, they use a decoder $\mathcal{D}(\cdot)$ to decode the latent representation $\mathbf{z}$ to the image space, which can be formally written as $\hat{\mathbf{x}}=\mathcal{D}(\mathbf{z})$. In practical use, we synthesize images by using the text prompts' embeddings of label $y \in \mathcal{Y}$ for guidance.

### 3.2. Latent Space Outlier Synthesis

To inherit the advantage of NPOS which does not require making distributional assumption on the model's ID feature space, we still apply non-parametric nearest neighbor distance to draw OOD embeddings from a large vision model. Then, to facilitate the overall outlier training process of the diffusion-based outlier synthesis method, when using Stable Diffusion to generate outliers, we utilize only its latent representation as the final synthesized data rather than the image it produces in pixel space.
OOD features sampling using k-NN. To reduce the overall training time, we directly employ k-NN to sample outliers

![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)

Figure 3. The overview of our OAL training pipeline for enhancing OOD detection. In stage 1, we first utilize k-NN distance search and Stable Diffusion to synthesize outliers in the latent space. Then, in stage 2, we develop a series of learning modules to regularize the model's decision boundary and boost its OOD detection performance by using the synthesized outliers. Note that, in the figure above, MICL represents the Mutual Information-based Contrastive Learning module. ‘RD.’ denotes response distillation. Score (·) denotes the score function used in the OOD inference phase. Besides, in OAL, the score function used for detecting OOD samples is taken as EBO [25].
from the in-distribution features extracted by a pre-trained vision transformer [8], which has already achieved superior performance on ID image classification tasks.

Specifically, denote $\mathbb{Z}=\left\{z_{1}, z_{2}, \cdots, z_{n}\right\}$ as the set of the normalized in-distribution training data feature vectors extracted by the pre-trained transformers, $z_{i} \in \mathbb{R}^{D}, D$ is the dimension of the transformer's penultimate layer's feature space. Then, for any $z^{\prime} \in \mathbb{Z}$, we calculate the k-NN distance with respect to $\mathbb{Z}$, that is,

$$
d_{k}\left(z^{\prime}, z_{k}\right)=\left\|z^{\prime}-z_{k}\right\|_{2}
$$

where $z_{k}$ is the k-th nearest embedding vectors in $\mathbb{Z}$, and $z_{k}^{*}$ is the vector with max k-NN distance. We select topk points with the largest k-NN distance as the boundary point of ID data. We denote these boundary points as $\hat{\mathbb{Z}}=\left\{z_{i}^{*}\right\}_{i=1}^{k}$. Afterwards, for each class $c \in \mathcal{Y}$, we take $\hat{z}_{i}^{*}:=\|\mathcal{T}(c)\|_{F} \cdot z_{i}^{*}(i=1, \cdots, k)$ as the center point of Gaussian kernels $\mathcal{N}\left(\hat{z}_{i}^{*}, \sigma^{2} \mathbf{I}\right)$ to repeatedly sample classconditioned OOD features from them, wherein $\mathcal{T}(c)$ is the text embedding of the name of class $c,\|\cdot\|_{F}$ is the Frobenius norm. We denote these OOD features sampled around $\hat{z}_{i}^{*}$
as $\mathbb{V}_{i}=\left\{\mathbf{v}_{1}, \cdots, \mathbf{v}_{m}\right\}(i=1, \cdots, k)$. To ensure the collected points are far away from the ID data, we apply k-NN distance search again to select data in $\mathbb{V}_{i}$ with top-k k-NN distance concerning $\mathbb{Z}$. We denote the final outliers sampled by k-NN as $\tilde{\mathbb{V}}=\left\{\tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{1}, \cdots, \tilde{\mathbf{v}}_{l}\right\}, l$ is a positive integer.
OOD latent embedding synthesis. In this section, to reduce the computational cost of the Diffusion-based outlier synthesis approaches and to obtain more diverse OOD samples for achieving higher OOD detection performance [31], we further develop a latent-based outlier synthesis module using Stable Diffusion.

The process of this module is simple. To be specific, we first take outlier embeddings $\tilde{\mathbf{v}} \in \tilde{\mathbb{V}}$ as the guidance to synthesize OOD images. However, in this study, we do not collect the final image outputs. Instead, we collect the latent representations $\mathbf{z}^{o o d}$ that are output during the generation process of the OOD image, which can be formulated as follows:

$$
\mathbf{z}^{o o d} \sim \tilde{P}(\mathbf{x} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{v}})
$$

where $\mathbf{z}^{o o d} \in \mathbb{R}^{c \times h \times w}, c$ is the number of channels, $h$ is

the height of the generated latent representations, $w$ is the width of the generated representations, $\mathbf{x}$ is the input image, $\tilde{P}(\mathbf{x} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{v}})$ is the distribution of the $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$ conditioned latent space.

After the generation step, we average the first two dimensions of $\mathbf{z}^{\text {ood }}$ to obtain the final OOD latent embeddings

$$
f^{\text {ood }}=\operatorname{Mean}\left(\mathbf{z}^{\text {ood }}\right)
$$

to train the model. In equation (1), $\operatorname{Mean}(\cdot)$ denotes the operator that takes the average of the first two dimensions of $\mathbf{z}^{\text {ood }}$.

### 3.3. OOD Aware Model Regularization

To effectively regularize the model's decision boundary between ID and OOD features, we develop a contrastive learning module, named as MICL, instead of using energy-based uncertainty loss function [10, 46]. Moreover, we develop a knowledge distillation module, named IDKD, for boosting the model's in-distribution classification performance.
Mutual information-based contrastive learning. Inspired by CLUB [4], we develop a mutual information-based contrastive learning module to enlarge the discrepancy between ID and OOD data in the feature space. To be specific, we propose a learning technique that minimizes the upper bound of mutual information between ID and OOD features, making them more independent of each other. We name it
as MICL (Mutual Information Contrastive Learning). In our work, we apply the theory proposed by CLUB to regularize the model using the synthesized OOD data.

To this end, we use mutual information to quantify the distance between the ID and OOD feature distribution, which takes the form as follows,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tilde{\mathbf{u}} & =\phi_{\theta}(\tilde{\mathbf{v}}) \\
I\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right) & =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log \frac{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where $f^{i n} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ is the penultimate layer's feature of the student network, which is the ResNet-18 shown in Figure $3, \tilde{\mathbf{v}} \in \tilde{\mathrm{V}}$ denotes the OOD embeddings sampled by $\mathrm{k}-\mathrm{NN}$. $\phi_{\theta}: \mathbb{R}^{D} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{d}$ is a fully connected neural network that aligns $\tilde{\mathbf{v}}$ and $f^{i n}$ into the same feature space.

Similarly, the mutual information between outliers $f^{\text {ood }} \in \mathbb{R}^{w}$ synthesized by Stable Diffusion and $f^{i n}$ can be written as the following,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\tilde{f}^{\text {ood }} & =\phi_{\theta}^{\prime}\left(f^{\text {ood }}\right) \\
I\left(\tilde{f}^{\text {ood }} ; f^{i n}\right) & =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{f}^{\text {ood }}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log \frac{p\left(\tilde{f}^{\text {ood }}, f^{i n}\right)}{p\left(\tilde{f}^{\text {ood }}\right) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\phi_{\theta}^{\prime}: \mathbb{R}^{w} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{d}$ is also a fully connected neural network that projects $f^{\text {ood }}$ into the same feature space as $f^{i n}$.

![table_2](table_2)

Let

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{MI}}\left(f^{i n}, \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right) & :=\tilde{I}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right) \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)] \\
& -\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}})} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)] \\
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{MI}}\left(f^{i n}, \tilde{f}^{o o d}\right) & :=\tilde{I}\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d} ; f^{i n}\right) \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d} ; f^{i n}\right)}[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{f}^{o o d}\right)] \\
& -\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d}\right)} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{f}^{o o d}\right)]
\end{aligned}
$$

We use MICL1 and MICL2 as the loss functions to regularize the model with synthesized data.

Indeed, one can directly show that $\tilde{I}\left(\mathbf{u} ; f^{i n}\right)$ and $\tilde{I}\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d} ; f^{i n}\right)$ are upper bounds of $I\left(\mathbf{u} ; f^{i n}\right)$ and $I\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d} ; f^{i n}\right)$ by calculating the gaps between them. We summarize this fact in the following Theorem.

Theorem 1. Based on the discussions above, we have the following inequalities,

- (i) $I\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right) \leqslant \tilde{I}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right)$ with equality if and only if $\tilde{\mathbf{u}}$ and $\tilde{f}^{i n}$ are independent;
- (ii) $I\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d} ; f^{i n}\right) \leqslant \tilde{I}\left(\tilde{f}^{o o d} ; f^{i n}\right)$ with equality if and only if $\tilde{f}^{o o d}$ and $f^{i n}$ are independent.

In-distribution performance boosting by knowledge distillation. Besides using mutual information-based loss function to enlarge feature discrepancies, we develop InDistribution Knowledge Distillation module to prevent the ID accuracy degradation when training with outliers. We refer to this module as IDKD for brevity.

In IDKD, we first leverage KL divergence loss to allow the student network to mimic the teacher network's logits outputs, which can be formulated as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{KL}}^{1}\left(\hat{y}_{S}^{\prime}, \hat{y}_{T}\right) & =\int_{\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{X}} \ln \left(\frac{\hat{y}_{S}^{\prime}}{\hat{y}_{T}}\right) \hat{y}_{S}^{\prime} d \mathbf{x} \\
\hat{y}_{S}^{\prime} & =\operatorname{Softmax}\left(\hat{y}_{S}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\hat{y}_{S}$ is the logits output of the student model, $\hat{y}_{T}$ is the softmax prediction of the teacher model.

Then, to transfer ID information at the feature level, we develop a domain transfer network consisting of a stack of Multi-Layer Perceptrons (MLPs) to align the teacher model's

Table 4. Ablation of the modules in OAL on the CIFAR-100 benchmark using EBO score.

![table_3](table_3)

feature spaces with the student model's penultimate layer's feature space. Formally, we denote the domain transfer network as $\varphi(\cdot): \mathbb{R}^{D} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{d}, D>d$. Then, the learning objective function for minimizing the distribution discrepancy between the teacher model's feature and the student model's feature can be written as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{KL}}^{2}\left(\tilde{f}^{i n}, \tilde{f}_{T}^{i n}\right) & =\int_{\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{X}} \ln \left(\frac{\tilde{f}^{i n}}{\tilde{f}_{T}^{i n}}\right) \tilde{f}^{i n} d \mathbf{x} \\
\tilde{f}_{T}^{i n} & =\operatorname{Softmax}\left(\varphi\left(f_{T}^{i n}\right)\right) \\
\tilde{f}^{i n} & =\operatorname{Softmax}\left(f^{i n}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $f^{i n}$ is the in-distribution feature of the student model, $f_{T}^{i n}$ is the ID feature extracted by the teacher model.

Finally, the total loss function takes the form as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {total }} & =\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{CE}}\left(\hat{y}_{S}, y_{g t}\right)+\alpha_{1} \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{KL}}^{1}\left(\hat{y}_{S}^{\prime}, \hat{y}_{T}\right) \\
& +\alpha_{2} \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{KL}}^{2}\left(\tilde{f}^{i n}, \tilde{f}_{T}^{i n}\right)+\beta \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{MI}}\left(f^{i n}, \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right) \\
& +\gamma \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{MI}}\left(f^{i n}, \tilde{f}^{o o d}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $y_{g t}$ is the ground truth, $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \beta, \gamma$ are the weights of each component of $\mathcal{L}_{\text {total }}, \mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{CE}}$ is the cross-entropy loss, $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{KL}}^{1}$ is the KL-divergence loss between the logits output of the student and teacher network, $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{KL}}^{2}$ is the KL-divergence loss between the feature output of student and teacher network.

## 4. Experiments
### 4.1. Experimental Setup

Datasets. We evaluate our methods on two commonly used benchmarks: CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 [20]. On the CIFAR-10 benchmark, we take CIFAR-10 [20] as the ID data, CIFAR-100 [20], TIN (Tiny ImageNet) [21], MNIST [6], SVHN [33], Texture [5], Places365 [54] as the OOD datasets. When using CIFAR-100 [20] as the ID dataset, we use CIFAR-10 [20], TIN [21], MNIST [6], SVHN [33], Texture [5], Places365 [54] as the OOD datasets.
Evaluation metrics. To evaluate the performance of OOD detection, we use 3 commonly used metrics following [11, 46]: (i) the False Positive Rate (FPR) at 95\% True Positive Rate; (ii) the Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve (AUROC); (iii) the in-distribution classification accuracy (ID ACC) of the tested models.

Table 5. Ablation analysis of the backbone, taking CIFAR-100 as the in-distribution dataset.

![table_4](table_4)

Implementation details. We choose ResNet-18 [14] as the backbone of the student model, ViT-B/16 [8] as the backbone of the teacher model. We run all experiments using Python 3.8.19, Pytorch 1.13.1 with one V100 GPU. Our code is developed mainly based on OpenOOD [50, 52]. To facilitate the implementation of knowledge distillation, we set both the train and test image resolution to $224 \times 224$ for all methods on CIFAR-10/100 [20] benchmarks. To ensure fairness, the train batch size of all methods is set to 128 and the validation and test batch size are set to 200. For both CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 datasets [20], the training epoch of our method is set to 100 and the learning rate is set to 0.005 using SGD [35] as the optimizer. The weights in loss function (4) for both CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 are set to $\alpha_{1}=4.0, \alpha_{2}=8.0$, $\beta=0.1, \gamma=0.2$, respectively. We generate 300 OOD latent embeddings using Stable Diffusion v1.4 taking CIFAR10/100 as the ID data. In addition, we do not apply any test time augmentation or data augmentation techniques.
Baselines. To evaluate the post hoc-based baselines, such as MSP [15], ODIN [24], Gram [38], EBO [25], ReAct [43], ViM [47], KNN [44], GEN [26], we directly use the settings given in OpenOOD [50, 52] with the same pretrained ResNet-18 backbone. In ODIN, the temperature is set to $T=1000$. For EBO, the temperature is set to $T=1$. For both VOS [10] and NPOS [46], we sample 1000 points for each class following the original settings given in OpenOOD $[50,52]$.

### 4.2. Main Results

To demonstrate the efficacy of our methods, we apply OAL to the EBO [25] score and test the method on CIFAR-100 and CIFAR-10 [20] benchmarks. The other outlier synthesisbased methods, listed in Tables 1 and 2, are all tested using ResNet-18 as the backbone and EBO as the score function. Evaluation on CIFAR-100. From Table 1, we can observe that OAL outperforms other outlier exposure-based methods, such as VOS [10] and NPOS [46], as well as post hoc methods (e.g., MSP, MDS, ViM) with a certain margin. Specifically, we can observe that OAL outperforms VOS by $9.00 \%$ in mean FPR@95 and by $4.72 \%$ in mean AUROC. It also outperforms NPOS by $40.51 \%$ in mean FPR@95 and by $31.17 \%$ in mean AUROC. Besides, OAL surpasses EBO by $4.53 \%$ in FPR@95 and by $2.51 \%$ in AUROC, averaged

Evaluation on CIFAR-10. As shown in Table 2, OAL also achieves the best performance among all post hoc and outlier synthesis-based approaches. To be specific, OAL outperforms VOS by $4.33 \%$ in mean FPR@95 and by $1.39 \%$ in mean AUROC. It also outperforms EBO by $5.33 \%$ in mean FPR@95 and by $1.51 \%$ in mean AUROC.
Comparisons with other outlier synthesis-based approaches. Furthermore, we perform comparisons between OAL and other outlier synthesis-based methods, such as GAN [22], Dream-OOD [11], and ATOL [53], in Table 3. As shown in Table 3, OAL's mean FPR@95 is $16.49 \%$ lower than Dream-OOD's on SVHN. Besides, OAL outperforms Dream-OOD by $29.71 \%$ in FPR@95 and by $7.68 \%$ in AUROC on Places365.
Comparison of computational costs. Herein, we test the computational cost of OAL and other baselines on the CIFAR-100 benchmark. The results are summarized as follows: the post hoc methods require training a model on in-distribution data for 2.4 hours; VOS takes 12.6 hours for training; in Dream-OOD, as the authors stated in the paper, their approach requires learning the text-conditioned latent space for about 8.2 hours, 10.1 hours for generating 100 K images, and 8.5 more hours to train with synthesized OOD data; while our approach only requires 0.5 hours to generate the outliers and the train time of our methods OAL takes about 8.7 hours. This result further supports our statement that synthesizing OOD data in the latent space using Stable Diffusion benefits the overall outlier exposure training

### 4.3. Ablation Study

Ablation of the learning framework. Here we investigate the impact of each component of our learning framework on the CIFAR-100 [20] benchmark. The results are shown in Table 4. In Table 4, setting (v-1) represents the best results of OAL across 3 training runs, and setting (v-2) reports the mean $\pm$ standard deviation value of OAL across 3 training runs. As shown in Table 4, the comparison between setting (iii) and setting (v-1) shows the effectiveness of using OOD data synthesized by Diffusion for outlier exposure training. By comparing setting (iv) with setting (v-1) and (v-2), we can find that IDKD improves both the ID accuracy and the OOD detection performance of the model to a great extent. By comparing setting (ii) with (v-1) and (v-2), we can find that the combination of IDKD and MICL blocks significantly improves the OOD detection results.
Ablation on the backbone. In this section, we analyze the impact of changes to the backbone. The results are shown in Table 5. From Table 5 we can find that OAL is effective for both ResNet-18 and ResNet-50 using EBO score as the OOD detector, verifying that OAL is robust to backbone change.
Ablation of score functions. To analyze the versatility of our methods, we further apply OAL to MSP [15] and GEN [26] (the softmax-based), KNN [44] (the distance-based) on the CIFAR-100 benchmark. As shown in Table 6, OAL works well for GEN [26] score and EBO [25] score. For MSP and KNN, we observe that the mean FPR @ 95 and AUROC decrease after using OAL for training the network. Therefore, our experiment results imply that OAL may has a positive impact on the softmax-based and the energy-based post hoc methods and has negative impact on the distancebased approaches.

### 4.4. Score Distribution Visualization

In this section, we aim to explore the effect of OAL training on the score distribution using EBO score. To this end, we visualize the score distribution of EBO using CIFAR-100 as the in-distribution data and Texture as the OOD data under the vanilla training, the VOS training, and OAL training, respectively. As shown in Figure 5, OAL reduces the overlap areas between the ID and OOD score distributions more than VOS does on the Texture dataset. This indicates that OAL has a stronger ability to enhance EBO's OOD detection performance than VOS. Additionally, we observe that the standard deviation of the estimated scores on both ID and OOD data is reduced considerably after applying OAL, highlighting another advantage of our method, i.e., OAL makes EBO produce more accurate OOD scores for test samples.

## 5. Conclusion

In this work, to facilitate the training of the outlier synthesisbased methods using Stable Diffusion, we introduce a novel outlier synthesis and training framework, named as OAL.

To be specific, we facilitate model learning by synthesizing OOD features from the latent space of Stable Diffusion and develop a mutual information-based contrastive learning module to effectively regularize the decision boundary between ID and OOD data. Moreover, we develop knowledge distillation blocks to prevent degradation in ID classification accuracy while simultaneously enhancing OOD detection. The experiments on the CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 benchmarks show that OAL outperforms many state-of-the-art post hoc methods and outlier synthesis-based methods, demonstrating the effectiveness of our proposed framework.

## Appendix
## A. Proof for Theorem 1

Proof. For the first inequality in Theorem 1, $I$ and $\hat{I}$ can be written as the following form:

$$
\begin{aligned}
I\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right) & =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log \frac{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\right] \\
\hat{I}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right) & =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right] \\
& -\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}})} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Denote

$$
\Delta:=\hat{I}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right)-I\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right)
$$

then, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta & =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]-\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}})} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right] \\
& -\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log \frac{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\right] \\
& =\left[\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]-\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}})} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]\right] \\
& -\left[\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]-\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n}\right)\right]\right] \\
& =\left[\mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n}\right)\right]-\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}})} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]\right] \\
& -\left[\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right]-\mathbb{E}_{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right]\right.\right. \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n}\right)\right]-\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}})} \mathbb{E}_{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)\right] \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log \frac{p\left(f^{i n}\right)}{p\left(f^{i n} \mid \tilde{\mathbf{u}}\right)}\right] \\
& =\mathbb{E}_{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}\left[\log \frac{p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)}{p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)}\right] \\
& =\mathrm{KL}\left(p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right) \| p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Herein, $\mathrm{KL}(\cdot \mid \mid \cdot)$ denotes the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence. By Theorem 6.2.1 in [32], we have $\Delta \geq 0$. Therefore, $I\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right)$ is an upper bound of $I\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}} ; f^{i n}\right)$. Meanwhile, the equality achieves if and only if $p(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}) p\left(f^{i n}\right)=p\left(\tilde{\mathbf{u}}, f^{i n}\right)$, i.e., $\tilde{\mathbf{u}}$ and $f^{i n}$ are independent.

The similar calculation can be done for the second inequality in Theorem 1. We omit it here.

abstract:
Numerous Out-of-Distribution (OOD) detection algorithms have been developed
to identify unknown samples or objects in real-world deployments. One line of
work related to OOD detection propose utilizing auxiliary datasets to train OOD
detectors, thereby enhancing the performance of OOD detection. Recently,
researchers propose to leverage Stable Diffusion (SD) to generate outliers in
the pixel space, which may complicate network training. To mitigate this issue,
we propose an Outlier Aware Learning (OAL) framework, which synthesizes OOD
training data in the latent space. This improvement enables us to train the
network with only a few synthesized outliers. Besides, to regularize the
model's decision boundary, we develop a mutual information-based contrastive
learning module (MICL) that amplifies the distinction between In-Distribution
(ID) and collected OOD features. Moreover, we develop a knowledge distillation
module to prevent the degradation of ID classification accuracy when training
with OOD data. Extensive experiments on CIFAR-10/100 benchmarks demonstrate the
superior performance of our method.
